<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a> Moletsene said the latest incident happened last week when he tried to report a crime that took place in his area but was sent home after the cops called him ugly.   “Every time I want to open a case, they just laugh at me and tell me to go home and sleep,” he said.   “Once an officer told me I’m ugly and he wouldn’t help me. I’m so hurt by all this because I’m a normal person.”   Moletsene said the police refused to help him when a stranger stole a piece of land next to his yard  which he was planning to plant vegetables on.    He said the stranger turned it into a soccer field.    “All I wanted was to plough and plant vegetables on the piece of land I had been allocated. Before I could do this, I found kids and a stranger playing soccer on it,” he said.   “When I went to the police they just ignored me as always and turned me away. I need help.”   Police spokesman Vuyo Mhaga said: “We condemn the alleged behaviour of the police.  Every South African has the right to be served with dignity and respect.   We are going to follow up the matter to get to the bottom of it.   “We will also communicate with the complainant.”